# Complete Implementation

```cpp
#include <hexi/detail/intrusive_storage.h>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>
#include <algorithm>

template<size_t block_size = 1024>
std::vector<uint8_t> preview_data_without_consuming(const hexi::detail::intrusive_storage<block_size>& storage, size_t bytes_to_preview) {
    // Get the amount of readable data available
    size_t readable = storage.readable_size();

    // Limit preview size to available data
    size_t to_copy = std::min(bytes_to_preview, readable);

    // Create result vector with appropriate size
    std::vector<uint8_t> result(to_copy);

    // Copy data without consuming (peek instead of read)
    if (to_copy > 0) {
        storage.peek(result.data(), to_copy);
    }

    return result;
}

template<size_t block_size = 1024>
struct BufferStatus {
    size_t readable_size;
    size_t free_space;
};

template<size_t block_size = 1024>
BufferStatus<block_size> check_buffer_status(const hexi::detail::intrusive_storage<block_size>& storage) {
    BufferStatus<block_size> status;

    // Get readable data size (data available to read)
    status.readable_size = storage.readable_size();

    // Get writable space (free space available for writing)
    status.free_space = storage.writable_size();

    return status;
}

template<size_t block_size = 1024>
void reset_buffer(hexi::detail::intrusive_storage<block_size>& storage) {
    // Reset both read and write offsets to clear the buffer
    storage.clear();
}
```

## Explanation:

1. **`preview_data_without_consuming`**:
   - Uses `readable_size()` to determine how much data is available
   - Limits the preview to the smaller of requested bytes or available data
   - Uses `peek()` to copy data without advancing the read pointer
   - Returns a vector containing the previewed data

2. **`check_buffer_status`**:
   - Uses `readable_size()` to get the amount of data that can be read
   - Uses `writable_size()` to get the amount of free space available for writing
   - Returns a `BufferStatus` struct with both values

3. **`reset_buffer`**:
   - Uses `clear()` to reset both read and write offsets, effectively emptying the buffer
   - This makes all space writable again and sets readable size to 0

